Eleven of fourteen patients requiring invasive ventilation developed severe hypoxemia postintubation despite application of volume-cycled ventilation with high PEEP or APRV leading to proning maneuvers (Table 2
). Airway pressure release ventilation alone was not helpful in reversing hypoxemia refractory to conventional low-stretch tidal ventilation (Table 3
). Airway pressure release ventilation was done per protocol demonstrated previously by Habashi.7 Proning was done per manufacturer’s protocol for automated rotational proning.8 Typically proning at our institution is initiated after 48 hours of ICU stay for intubated patients with extensive radiographic infiltrates requiring an FiO2 of more than 0.6 and PEEPs of more than 12 on volume-cycled ventilation. However, in patients with 2009 pandemic influenza (H1N1) pneumonia, proning was initiated much earlier due to severe hypoxemia despite high airway pressures and FiO2s (Tables 2 and 3). The mean time to initiation of proning for the 4 proned patients in the first wave of the H1N1 pandemic was 59 hours (range 6-106 hours). For the 7 patients proned in the second wave of the pandemic, the mean time to initiation of proning was 7 hours (range 3-14 hours). Proning was discontinued if patients showed an ability to maintain oxygenation for 12 to 24 hours in supine position using FiO2 of less than 0.6. The mean duration of proning was 111 hours (range 63-203 hours).
